🧪 1. Add Example Inputs
Why this matters first: One of the biggest friction points for any new user is not knowing what "good input" looks like. Without examples, users often provide vague or malformed text, get underwhelming structured output, and assume the app doesn't work well—when in reality it just needed better input to begin with. Examples solve this upstream. They also make the app feel immediately alive and usable the moment someone opens it.
