📅 Meeting notes example: "Sync with the design team tomorrow at 10am to review the new onboarding wireframes. Make sure to bring feedback from last sprint. Follow up with Sarah about the copy revisions by Thursday EOD."
🛒 Grocery / errand list: "Pick up milk, eggs, sourdough bread, and almond butter from Publix before Friday. Also need to return the Amazon package and drop off dry cleaning."
💼 Professional project tasks: "Q2 strategy doc needs to be finalized by April 15th. Coordinate with Dev, Design, and Marketing leads. Schedule kick-off meeting for next Monday morning."
🏠 Home / life tasks: "Fix the leaky bathroom faucet this weekend. Call the HOA about the parking permit. Renew car registration before May 1st."
Ideally, implement this as a horizontal scrollable chip row or a dropdown selector labeled "Load an Example" sitting directly above or below the input textarea. Each chip should be labeled with a short category title (e.g., "📅 Meeting Notes", "🛒 Errands", "💼 Project Tasks") so users can instantly understand what they'll get. When clicked, the example text populates the textarea and the "Process" button becomes immediately active.
This single feature drastically improves first-run experience, makes the app feel polished and guided rather than blank and intimidating, and gives users a mental model for how to write effective inputs on their own.
🛡️ 2. Improve Error Handling
Why this matters: Right now, if the Gemini API encounters an issue—whether it's a rate limit, a network timeout, a malformed response, or an empty result—the user receives either a cryptic error dump, a blank output panel, or no feedback at all. This creates confusion, erodes trust in the tool, and provides no path forward. Robust error handling is one of the clearest signals of a production-quality application vs. a prototype.
What I'm requesting:
🔴 API failure states: Wrap all Gemini API calls in try/catch with graceful fallback UI. If the API fails, display a friendly inline message in the output panel such as: "Gemini couldn't process your request right now. This might be a temporary issue—please try again in a moment." Include a visible 🔁 Retry button directly below the message.
⏳ Loading state: Add an animated loading indicator (spinner or pulsing skeleton) in the output panel while processing is underway. This reassures the user that work is happening. Currently the app can appear frozen during longer API calls.
📭 Empty output handling: If the API returns a valid response but with no actionable tasks detected, display a helpful message like: "No structured tasks were found. Try adding more context, action verbs, or dates to your input." Never show a blank output panel—it's always ambiguous whether something failed or just had nothing to return.
⚠️ Network/offline detection: Use the browser's navigator.onLine API combined with an online/offline event listener to detect connectivity. If the user is offline, immediately disable the Process button and show a banner: "You're currently offline. Processing will resume once your connection is restored."
🗂️ Draft auto-save: If processing fails mid-way or the user accidentally clears the textarea, preserve their last typed input in a JS in-memory variable (avoid localStorage since the app runs in a sandboxed iframe). Show a subtle "Restore last input" link that re-populates the textarea.
✅ 3. Add Input Validation
Why this matters: Sending empty, too-short, or malformed input to the Gemini API wastes API quota, produces useless output, and adds latency for no reason. Client-side validation should act as a smart gatekeeper—catching obvious issues before they ever hit the API—and as a coach that guides users toward better inputs.
What I'm requesting:
Implement a real-time validation layer that evaluates input as the user types and provides contextual feedback:
Empty input check: Disable the "Process" button by default. Only enable it once the textarea contains at least 15–20 meaningful characters.
Too-short warning: If the user submits fewer than 15 characters, display an inline message: "Your input is too short. Add more detail—dates, names, deadlines, or action items work best."
Too-long warning: For inputs exceeding 6,000 characters, show a yellow advisory: "Your input is quite long. For best results, consider breaking it into separate sessions." Optionally show a live character count (e.g., 2,340 / 6,000 chars) in the corner of the textarea.
Duplicate detection: If the user submits the same input twice within a session, prompt them: "This looks identical to your last input. Would you like to reprocess it, or did you want to modify it first?"
